WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
In this video, we will look at the main risks of using AI,

2
00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.000
what responsible use means in our daily work,

3
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.500
and the internal policy that defines how we use AI at H&dM.

4
00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:15.000
AI is powerful, but it is not neutral, objective,
or automatically correct.

5
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Every AI output needs human oversight.

6
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Two of the most important risks are bias and hallucination.

7
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Bias means that an AI system may reproduce patterns,
assumptions, exclusions, or stereotypes

8
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
from the data it was trained on.

9
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.500
For example, an image model asked to visualize
an "office worker"

10
00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:39.000
might repeatedly show the same age, gender,
or cultural background,

11
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:40.000
excluding other realities.

12
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Hallucination means that an AI system may produce information

13
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
that sounds plausible but is inaccurate,
incomplete, or simply invented.

14
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
For example, a language model might invent
a building-code requirement,

15
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
a project reference, or a quotation
that does not actually exist.

16
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
This is especially important in architectural practice,
where factual, technical,

17
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.500
regulatory, and contextual accuracy matters.

18
00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:08.000
This is why we remain responsible for reviewing, correcting,

19
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
adapting, and deciding what is used.

20
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
AI should never be a justification for technical mistakes,

21
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:19.000
poor quality or work that does not align
with H&dM's values and the intent of a project.

22
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Transparency is essential.

23
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.000
We must not present AI-generated or AI-enhanced work
as purely human if it is not.

24
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
Another important factor is environmental impact.

25
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
AI tools consume computing resources, energy, and water.

26
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
This has both financial and environmental consequences.

27
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.500
Responsible use means prompting with intent,
generating only what is useful,

28
00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:46.000
and treating computing resources as shared and finite,
just like physical resources in the office.

29
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
There are also legal and regulatory responsibilities.

30
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Client data, project information, and personal data
are protected by laws

31
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.000
such as the EU GDPR, the Swiss FADP, and the EU AI Act.

32
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:04.000
This means we need to be careful about what information
we enter into AI tools,

33
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.500
especially when working with confidential project material,

34
00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:12.000
client information, contracts, briefs, drawings,
models, or internal reports.

35
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
To manage these risks, H&dM has an internal AI Policy

36
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
combined with an index of approved AI services.

37
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.500
Within this framework we are safe to use AI
with a level of security

38
00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:26.000
that applies to H&dM standards.

39
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
In the next section, we will break this framework down
into six core usage principles:

40
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.500
Human Accountability, Design Quality, Authorship & IP,

41
00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:37.000
Efficient Use, Security and Transparency.
